<p>And you‚Äôre not limited to static graphics. Check out the gif on Loomly‚Äôs landing page for social media tools.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-loomly-gif.png" alt="landing page trends - example of a gif by loomly" width="720" height="313" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-69572 aligncenter" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-loomly-gif.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-loomly-gif-480x209.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em><a href="https://go.loomly.com/social-media-tools/?utm_source=google&amp;utm_medium=cpc&amp;utm_campaign=1618592057&amp;utm_content=62028842820&amp;utm_term=social%20media%20tools&amp;gclid=CjwKCAiA8OmdBhAgEiwAShr40xHEPrxWxbZO-Z-aa4pgOL4r-hoWP6QWY4ZQvT6vwEhv_emkk8NbrxoCqdQQAvD_BwE" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Image source |</a> <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-loomly.mp4" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Watch the video</a></em></p>
<p>Simple, effective, and worth trying out with your audience.<br />
<a id="simple"></a></p>
<h3>3. Simple, streamlined design</h3>
<p>Understated design for landing pages is a part of a larger branding trend that‚Äôs, well, counter-intuitive: <a href="https://www.envato.com/blog/graphic-design-trends/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">anti-branding</a>. Think monochromatic packaging, clean and unassuming color schemes, and minimal brand elements.</p>
<p>While the design style has been around for a while, it‚Äôs becoming more popular as <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/08/09/gen-z-stats">Gen-Z</a> buying power increases. Research suggests that this generation is, overall, skeptical of brands. <a href="https://www.edelman.com/trust/2022-trust-barometer/special-report-new-cascade-of-influence" target="_blank" rel="noopener">73%</a> Gen-Zers only buy from brands that they believe in.</p>
<p>Here‚Äôs a great example from Typeform‚Äôs landing page for easy-to-create surveys. The background is beige (and, uh, blah), and the buttons and font are both a standard black.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-typeform.png" alt="landing page trends - streamlined design by typeform" width="720" height="346" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-69560 aligncenter" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-typeform.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-typeform-480x231.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://try.typeform.com/survey-builder/?gclsrc=aw.ds&amp;&amp;tf_campaign=us_ca-generic-survey-english-desktop_17147702106&amp;tf_source=google&amp;tf_medium=paid&amp;tf_content=137266692918_596400465533&amp;tf_term=surveys&amp;tf_dv=c&amp;tf_matchtype=e&amp;tf_adposition=&amp;tf_location=1018127&amp;gclid=CjwKCAiA8OmdBhAgEiwAShr406X2s9yAZlKUDXyZVyUt5FFc1vXThpoIJL9PkZj5dSqa8dTP4fP_whoCfPcQAvD_BwE&amp;gclsrc=aw.ds" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Image source</em></a></p>
<p>The effect? Straight-to-the-point page that makes the tool <em>seem </em>easy. Simple design is still design, after all, and anti-branding is still branding.<br />
<a id="monochromatic"></a></p>
<h3>4. Monochromatic backgrounds</h3>
<p>If anti-branding doesn‚Äôt match your <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/03/31/brand-personality-messaging">brand personality</a>‚Äîor, for that matter, your target audience‚Äîyou can still keep it simple in 2023. Monochromatic website backgrounds are trending, and this style lends itself well to all of your landing pages. After all, you want your landing page skimmable and conversion-focused.</p>
<p>Take a look at Squarespace.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-squarespace.png" alt="landing page trends - monochromatic background example by squarespace" width="720" height="361" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-69561 aligncenter" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-squarespace.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-squarespace-480x241.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.squarespace.com/?channel=pnb&amp;subchannel=go&amp;campaign=pnb-go-us-en-core_comp_general_tier1-phr&amp;subcampaign=(mailchimp_mailchimp_phr)&amp;&amp;cid=13842267359&amp;aid=139711133505&amp;tid=aud-77699953542:kwd-65462921&amp;mt=p&amp;eid=&amp;loc_p_ms=1018127&amp;loc_i_ms=&amp;nw=g&amp;d=c&amp;adid=617163381528&amp;channel2=pnb&amp;subchannel2=go&amp;gclid=CjwKCAiA8OmdBhAgEiwAShr40-hmam__07MQIkg5QzCEQonHQuzZegvFQQRzPNy-rS8dEbUG4ZFPshoCO4gQAvD_BwE&amp;gclsrc=aw.ds" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Image source</em></a></p>
<p>The natural curves in the design add depth, but the monochromatic palette keeps it, well, as background. And of course the go-to self-serve website builder takes the color scheme and extends it to the landing page in the landing page. You love to see that attention to detail.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div class='et-box et-shadow'>
					<div class='et-box-content'><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/2734.png" alt="‚ú¥" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> <strong>Free guide: <a href="https://marketing.wordstream.com/WSContentDLHowToMakeGreatLandingPagesGuide.html?cid=Web_Any_InContentTextLink_LandingPages_HowToMakeGreatLandingPagesGuide_Download">How to Create Great Landing Pages (With Examples!)</a> </strong></div></div>
<p><a id="deepgreens"></a></p>
<h3>5. Deep greens</h3>
<p><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/07/12/color-psychology-marketing">Color psychology matters</a>. Pantone‚Äôs color for the year is a deep pink <a href="https://www.pantone.com/color-of-the-year/2023" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Viva Magenta</a>, and we‚Äôll see this in a few examples today (don‚Äôt skip ahead just ahead, just pay attention to the buttons in the next trend). But the hues we‚Äôre seeing everywhere are on the other side of the color wheel. Greens.</p>
<p>Green has been trending in <a href="https://www.apartmenttherapy.com/sage-green-color-of-the-year-trend-2022-37011516" target="_blank" rel="noopener">interior design</a> for a few years now, and it‚Äôs always been a popular brand color for <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/12/19/best-healthcare-website-design">healthcare</a> and wellness-related companies in particular. More recently, green has been everywhere‚Äîsee the Squarespace background above, and the Ellevest example below.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-ellevest.png" alt="landing page trends - deep greens example by ellevest" width="720" height="336" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-69562 aligncenter" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-ellevest.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-ellevest-480x224.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.ellevest.com/getstarted?ko_click_id=ko_496863bb219b9d580&amp;c1=%7Bc1%7D&amp;source=%7Bsource%7D&amp;kw=%7Bkw%7D&amp;cr5=%7Bcr5%7D&amp;cr7=%7Bcr7%7D&amp;cr6=%7Bcr6%7D&amp;utm_source=gaw&amp;utm_medium=paid-search&amp;utm_campaign=search-nw-usa-brandmembership&amp;utm_content=%7Bev_utm_content%7D&amp;placement=%7Bplacement%7D&amp;camp_det=%7Bcamp_det%7D&amp;geo=%7Bgeo%7D&amp;subj=%7Bsubj%7D&amp;desc=%7Bdescription%7D&amp;hd_text=%7Bhd_text%7D&amp;ad_text=%7Bad_text%7D&amp;img_txt=%7Bimg_txt%7D&amp;cta_txt=%7Bcta_txt%7D&amp;promo=%7Bpromo%7D&amp;live_date=%7Blive_date%7D&amp;lp=%7Blp%7D&amp;utm_term=ellevest" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Image source</em></a></p>
<p>Notice that these greens are rich, whether they‚Äôre jewel-toned or earthy. When you‚Äôre giving your landing page a refresh, consider adding some deep green tones for an updated look for 2023.</p>
<p><a id="playful"></a></p>
<h3>6. Playful buttons</h3>
<p>Trends in design or copy are great inspiration to experiment with, but at the end of the day the best landing page is a <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2019/10/08/event-landing-pages">high-converting landing page</a>.</p>
<p>But that doesn‚Äôt mean your buttons need to be perfunctory ‚Äúsubmit‚Äù or, for that matter, big and orange. In fact, Unbounce found that getting specific in the call to action button can improve the conversion rate by up to <a href="https://unbounce.com/conversion-rate-optimization/design-call-to-action-buttons/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">90%</a>. Changing up your CTA is a great way to start playing around with your landing page buttons</p>
<p>You can stick to creative copywriting, or you test out the design. Lemonade, a pet insurance company, does this so well. The landing page design features minimal black, white, and gray design with line-drawn cats and dogs in motion, plus the brand‚Äôs bright pink accents and buttons. And some of these elements interact on the page‚Äîincluding one of the little pets and the buttons.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-lemonade.png" alt="landing page trends - playful buttons example by lemonade" width="720" height="361" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-69564 aligncenter" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-lemonade.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-lemonade-480x241.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.lemonade.com/pet?utm_source=google-search-generic_pet_us_bau_prospect&amp;utm_medium=ua&amp;utm_campaign=12008312635&amp;utm_term=116389736375_%2Bpet%20%2Binsurance%20%2Bhealth_c&amp;utm_content=483815063651" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Image source</em></a></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em> </em><br />
<a id="micro"></a></p>
<h3>7. Micro animations</h3>
<p>Animation on your landing page is great for keeping your user‚Äôs attention and making the time on page memorable. (The pets from the Lemonade page? Adorable.) But animations can also help direct your user to interact with your page. Micro animations are <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2018/03/29/ux-conversion-rates">UX design</a> tools that guide a user to move further down the page or take an action. These are something you‚Äôll want to try out in 2023.</p>
<p>This could be as simple as links changing color when the user hovers over them as a subtle encouragement to click, or as complex as something like this submit button.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-buttons.png" alt="landing page trends - example of animated button" width="500" height="245" class="size-full wp-image-69571 aligncenter" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-buttons.png 500w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-buttons-480x235.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 500px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://dribbble.com/shots/4269554-Submit-Button" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>View the animation here.</em></a><a href="https://dribbble.com/shots/4269554-Submit-Button" target="_blank" rel="noopener"></a></p>
<p>Either way, I‚Äôd be surprised if these UX designs don‚Äôt nudge a few extra conversions for you this year.<br />
<a id="handwriting"></a></p>
<h3>8. Handwriting-like font and emphasis</h3>
<p>It‚Äôs early, but we‚Äôre already seeing some themes in design trends for this year: playful visuals with personality, understated branding that appears barely there, and minimalist marketing. The common thread here isn‚Äôt new: It‚Äôs humanizing brands to create a more personal interaction between potential customers and marketing materials.</p>
<p>Another related landing page design trend to this? Handwriting-like fonts and elements.</p>
<p>Here‚Äôs a great subtle example from <a href="https://flocksy.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Flocksy</a>, a graphic design subscription company.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-flocksy.png" alt="landing page trends - handwriting font example by flocksy" width="720" height="291" class="size-full wp-image-69565 aligncenter" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-flocksy.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-flocksy-480x194.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p><a id="succint"></a></p>
<h3>9. Bold, succinct copy</h3>
<p>Minimalist <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2020/01/22/marketing-copy">marketing copy</a> is all over the place, but most of us still need copy on our landing pages. So this year, choose your words selectively and make them count. Keep it short and make it bold.</p>
<p>MasterClass does this really well. (Not surprising, considering the oh-so-humble brand name.)</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-masterclass.png" alt="landing page trends - bold succinct copy by masterclass" width="720" height="378" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-69563 aligncenter" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-masterclass.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-masterclass-480x252.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /><a href="https://www.masterclass.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><br />
<em>Image source</em></a></p>
<p>The headline is the value proposition: Learn from masters at their craft quickly.</p>
<p>There‚Äôs very little copy on the rest of the page, because that‚Äôs the big, bold draw.</p>
<p><span><div class='et-box et-shadow'>
					<div class='et-box-content'><strong>Speaking of bold copy&#8230;</strong></span></p>
<p><strong>¬†<img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f4e3.png" alt="üì£" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> Free guide: <a href="https://marketing.wordstream.com/WSLIQContentDLWebsite36CallToActionPhrases.html?cid=Web_Any_InContentTextLink_36CallToActionPhrases_Download" class="waffle-rich-text-link">The 36 Best Call to Action Phrases (Ever)</a> </strong><span></div></div></span><br />
<a id="norisk"></a></p>
<h3>10. No risk free trials</h3>
<p>We can admit it: Even as marketers who know the purpose of free trials and the importance of stakes to encourage a real product test and convert a customer, putting in your credit card information for a tool you want to try is annoying. It just is!</p>
<p>That‚Äôs why brands who can avoid it are doing so. We‚Äôve seen a number of ‚Äúno risk‚Äù or ‚Äúno credit card required‚Äù disclaimers around email address forms for trails recently, and we think this is going to keep getting more popular. (Because it‚Äôs appealing, of course it is!)</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-no-risk-trials.png" alt="landing page trends - no risk free trial example by constant contact" width="720" height="387" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-69566 aligncenter" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-no-risk-trials.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-no-risk-trials-480x258.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.constantcontact.com/landing1/newsletter-software?&amp;cc=GOO-245720&amp;pn=search&amp;gclid=CjwKCAiA8OmdBhAgEiwAShr40_vCfJizehCzZGeBmq3PhSW2l4Y9m8SBgaX0rszl_1MnSWycKXKt3BoC5l0QAvD_BwE&amp;gclsrc=aw.ds" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Image source </em></a><br />
<a id="howto"></a></p>
<h3>11. How-to sections</h3>
<p>While the goal of any landing page is going to be to convert visitors, the content is going to vary. It could be a free trial promo. An event or webinar registration. A product overview to book a demo.</p>
<p>All of these could benefit from a how-to section.</p>
<p>People like visuals and lists to break down larger topics. In fact, Semrush found that pages with lists every 500 words get <a href="https://www.semrush.com/blog/anatomy-of-top-performing-articles/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">70%</a> more traffic. While your landing page isn‚Äôt an article or a blog post, it is a page you‚Äôre looking to drive traffic towards. An<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2014/08/14/increase-traffic-to-my-website"> increase in traffic</a> that significant is worth a shot.</p>
<p>Take a look at this example from Lettuce Grow.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-how-to-section.png" alt="landing page trends - how to section example" width="720" height="317" class="size-full wp-image-69567 aligncenter" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-how-to-section.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/landing-page-trends-how-to-section-480x211.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.lettucegrow.com/the-farmstand/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Image source</em></a></p>
<p>The pictures are eye-catching and display the product even if I‚Äôm not looking for an in-depth guide. The copy is super skimmable. And it makes the product look accessible and easy to use.</p>
<p>Breaking down your product or service in these crisp steps with compelling visuals and skimmable copy will help communicate to your landing page visitors what you‚Äôre offering and how well it works‚Äîeven when they‚Äôre not necessarily looking for a step-by-step.</p>
<h2>Test out these landing page trends in 2023</h2>
<p>These are the landing page trends that will be worth your while. Straightforward to implement, cost-conscious, and effective for boosting conversions. Here‚Äôs to starting 2023 off right‚Äîwith lots of creativity, and hopefully lots of conversions. We went through a lot here, so let‚Äôs recap the landing page trends:</p>
<ol>
<li>Exceptional product videos</li>
<li>Integrated landing page copy and design</li>
<li>Simple, streamlined design</li>
<li>Monochromatic backgrounds</li>
<li>Deep greens</li>
<li>Bold, succinct copy</li>
<li>Playful buttons</li>
<li>Micro animations</li>
<li>Handwriting-like font and elements</li>
<li>‚ÄúNo risk‚Äù free trials</li>
<li>How-to sections</li>
</ol>
<p>And remember, while the trends are important, don&#8217;t jump on them at the cost of following the fundamental landing page best practices. Use our <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/great-landing-pages">landing page guide</a> to make sure you&#8217;re hitting those too!</p>
<p>Interested in trends from other years? Check out our archive:</p>
